//In C++, the ternary or conditional operator(?:) is the shortest form of writing conditional
//statements
//It can be used as an inline conditional statement in place of if-else to execute code

//SYNTAX
//expression ? statement_1 : statement_2;
//(expression) ? statement_1: statement_2;
//The ternary operator works on three operands:
// expression: Condition to be evaluated
// statement_1: Statement that will be executed if expression evaluates to true
// statement_2: Statement to be executed if code evaluates to false

//ALTERNATIVE SYNTAX TO IF-ELSE
if(condition){
 statement1;
}
 else{
 statement2;
 }
//The ternary operator has the third lowest precedence, so expressions need to be used so as to avoid errors
//due to improper operator precedence management
